english:
  title: Preface to the Imperial Edicts Published
  author: Lee Cheom
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The sage kings of old delighted in heeding even humble words, and in aiding the virtue of others—desiring thereby to broaden perception and understand the sentiments of the common people.

    When Yang-chon Master Gwon was at the imperial court, the Grand Progenitor honored him with exceptional courtesy, allowing him to enter the Hall of Literary Profundity and to walk as equal among Liu Sanwu, Xu Guan, Jing Qing, Zhang Xin, and their peers. The Emperor commissioned him to write on assigned topics, first instructing him to discourse upon the rise and fall of our nation and the roads traveled through distant lands, then upon the geographical boundaries of our realm, the strength of our mountains and rivers, and neighboring foreign lands. Thus Master Gwon, probing the breadth of heaven and earth, discriminating inner and outer principles, wove into his verses the gratitude of our Eastern people for imperial cultivation. Upon completion, his work was presented—radiant in brilliance, resonant in sound. The Emperor, upon reading it, lavished praise and commanded that he tour the southern and northern quarters, viewing pavilions and monuments in their entirety. Thereafter, the Emperor himself composed three poems: "The Yalu," "The Ancient Capital," and "Liaodong"—profound and soaring, their luster gleaming like orbs of pearl. Through the encompassing transformation of his benevolence, ten thousand different voices arise, yet high and low, great and small each find their proper place. Heaven withholds nothing from creation, responding universally with perfect measure—revealing a serene and generous spirit, sincere intent. This is the joy of aiding the good.

    Upon his return eastward, Master Gwon, deeply moved by the Emperor's unceasing grace, carefully transcribed the imperial poems and responding verses, preserving them as an eternal treasure for his descendants. Whenever envoys from the Middle Kingdom arrived, he would present these works, seeking inscriptions from their hands. Scholars from Huai'an, Jining, and Panyang each contributed fine verses and writings. One day, the Crown Prince requested to examine the collection. After reviewing it, he remarked: "That one of our Eastern people should enter the imperial court, display his learning, and become known throughout the realm—such is exceedingly rare. How much more extraordinary that he should receive the imperial brush itself, his words vying with sun and moon for their brilliance! This must not fade into oblivion." He then commanded Minister Park Seok-myeong to present the matter to the State Council for publication and distribution. Master Gwon asked me to compose this preface.
